<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-604-994  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 604 994.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Spectrum  June 1990 v27 n6 p28(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Power and energy. (Looking ahead to a single Europe in 1992)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Zorpette, Glenn.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Europe is projected to dominate worldwide the design andmanufacture of electric power equipment by the end of the century.andO;This includes all three power-equipment categories: generation,transmission, and distribution.andP;  A number of mergers andacquisitions are underway, which will give the bigger Europeancompanies a continental stance.andP;  Combined-cycle generating plants,plants that use both gas and steam turbines, are expected to bethe next big area.andP;  Procurement directives from the EuropeanCommunities propose that EC manufacturers be able to freely sellheavy electric equipment all over the 12 member countries.andP;  Butthe utility companies will be allowed to ignore bids fromcompanies that manufactures less than 50 percent of theirequipment in the EC, which eliminates US electrical manufacturersfrom bidding.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     International TradeManufacturingPower PlantsElectrical Equipment IndustryEuropean Economic Community.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>